  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Hyperbole is deliberate exaggeration for emphasis or effect — saying more than is literally true in order to communicate the intensity of an experience. \u0026ldquo;I\u0026rsquo;ve told you a million times,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;the bag weighed a ton,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;I could eat a horse.\u0026rdquo; The reader understands that the statement is not factually accurate; that understanding is part of how hyperbole works.\nHyperbole communicates emotional truth through factual distortion. When a writer says \u0026ldquo;the line stretched to infinity,\u0026rdquo; they\u0026rsquo;re reporting what the wait felt like, not what it measured. This makes hyperbole a tool for pathos — it conveys the subjective experience of a situation in terms the reader can feel.\n",
